d 990\n7:30 Rise and Shnne\n7:40 Road Man\n7:45 Jolly Bill and Jane\n8:00 Phil Cook\n8:15 The Old Witches -8:30\nShopping About with Dor\northy Randall\n8:45 Popular Bits\n9:15 Parnassus Trio\n9:45 Mid-week service, Greater\nBoston Federation of Churches\nRev. Samuel M. Lindsay, Brook\nline Baptist church\n10:30 Stock quotations\n10:35 Manhatters\n10:45 Mary IaleMartin's House\nhold 11:00 U. S. Army band\n11:3 0 Tercentenarians\n11:55 State House Safety\n39S WJZ,. New York 760\n7:30 Rise and Shine, dance or-\nchestra\n7:45 Jolly Bill and Jane, chil\ndren's program\nS:00 Phil Cook in character\nsongs and dialogue\n8:15 The Old Witches, skit with\nMarcella Shields and Helen Han\ndin 8:30 The Headliners; novelty or\nchestra 8:45 Popular Bits\n9:15 Classic Trio\nlOO-The Manhatters; novelty or\nchestra 1(1:45 Mary Hale Martin's House\nhold Period\n1 1 :00 U. S. Army band\n11:30 The Recitalists\n12:00 Organ Melodies. AI Carney,\norganist\nThrough the Static\nThe first of a series of broadcasts\nto be known as the \"Farm and For\num\" which will be transmitted thrice\na week from station WTIC. was\nheard at noon today, with officials\nof several Connecticut state depart\nments taking part.\nThe new series is designed ex\npressly for members of ti WTIC\naudience interested in the promo\ntion of agriculture and domestic\nscience. They will be broadcast\neajh Tuesday, Thursday and Sat\nurday noon, and will consist o brief\ninformative talks by officials and ex-,\nperts in Agricultural and domestic\nfields, news from state and federal\nagricultural headquarters, market\nreports, weather forecasts and short\nentertainment features. These will\nbe interspersed with music by a\ngroup Of WTIC staff musicians. Wil\nliam Mackensen, who for more than\nfive years has been announcing agri\ncultural broadcasts from station\nWTIC, will announce the new 'sc\nries. Lou Bode, Jr., a member of the\nBand of a Thousand Melodies, heard\nevery afternoon on an NBC pro\ngram, needs a \"boarding-house\nreach\" to perform his duties. He\nplays three instruments, the saxo\nphone, clarinet and the baritone\nsaxophone during the performance\nLAZZARO\nMaster Hat Rebailder\nWell trained hands built your hat at the\nfactory and gave it that fine appearance\nyou so admired at purchase If it is now'\nsoiled, out of shape and unsightly, bring it\nto our shop and have Lazzaro, the master\nof hat rebuilding, bring back the original\nlife apd color without the slightest odor of\n\"Cleaning\".\nRebuilt by Lazzaro no better can it be.\nThe Modern Hat Shop\nNew Britain's Leading 1\nHat and Shoe Rebuilders\n38 CHURCH ST. TELEPHONE 6328\nDIXIE DUGAN THE KITCHEN CALLS\nHAVE YOU .SEEN MA DOCSMT 5 HE KNOWN 1 EEIES2 I S J TT-nc 77\"\nUNCIE RED DEVIL? I I WE'RE ttWtf .v's t,ia TuTTv 'ZsT' N. ,-fcOOCH! HOPE YOU v\nv Can't rmv he V at th roof J7J?tX CS'8Ik w i V f coRUtt 8E.EF\nand Is kept very busy reaching for\neach.\nArcaie Birkenholz, violin virtu\noso of th-National Broadcasting Co.,\nis a firm believer in the stringed\ninstruments, but he was forced to\nadmit their limitations in the face\nof an amazing request received inj\nBaltimore.\nWhile Birkenholz was appearing\nas soloist with the Baltimore Sym\nphony orchestra, a few of the \"first\nstrings'\" of the group were invited\nto spend the evening at the home\nof a well known chemical manufac\nturer. The four artists fell to play\ning, and after half an hour of im\npromptu concert Birkenholz asked\nthe host if there were any particu\nlar string quartet he would like to\nhear. Whereupon the business man\nbowled them over by requesting the\noverture to the opera \"Raymond\"!\n(7 Italian Specials\nNaples, Sept. 2 (UP) Giovanni\nLaudisio, 13, was near death by as\nphyxiation today as a result of a\nfire which damaged his father's toy\nshop in the section of Mercato.\nThe boy was trapped in a rear\nroom while his parents escaped.\nThe fire started from a short circuit\nand spread \"rapidly. Damages were\nestimated at nearly 100,000 lire.\nCampo Basso, Sept. 2 (UP) A\nmemorial to the Italian war dead\nwas unveiled at Trivento in the\npresence of the Podesta, Bishop\nAdinolfi, civil and military authori\nties, and a large crowd. The town\nwas decorated for the event.\nBari, Sept. 2 (UP) Adojfo Cola\nbella, of Foggia, his wife and two\ndaughters and another female rela\ntive were injured when their auto\nmobile overturned after colliding\nwith a wagon near Barletta.\nFlorence, Sepfc- 2 (UP) Marshal\nrecopi-Giraldi, numerous officials)\nand a large crowd of peasants at\ntended the unveiling of a monument\nti the war dead at Bettolle, near\nSinalunga.\nOstia, Sept. J, (UP) The first\ncamel to be transported by air\nplane in Italy arrived here Saturday\nfrom Tunis and proceeded to Rome\nto be placed in the too.\nAlessandro, Sept. 2 (UP) Albino\nCessaro, Gino Carradini,\" Lorenzi\nNicoli, and Giovanni Scoccia, stu\ndents in the Gregorian Catholic\nUniversity and the Lateran College\ni.i Rome arrived in the town of Tor\ntona after walking 850 kilometers\nfrom Rome, which they left July\n-28. They stopped at Assisi, Loretc-,\nand other sanctuaries along the\nroute The party will proceed on\nfoot to the mother house at Bra,\nprovince of Cuneo, for spiritual re\ntreat before they are ordained.\nTurin, Sept 2 (UP Miss Tatiana\nFumagalli a contestant in the air\nrace around Itly whose plane was\ndamaged when the machine of the\nEnglish woman flyer Miss Evelyn\nSpooner crashed itito it while land\ning at Vercelli Friday was ready to\ncontinue the race today following\nrepairs to her plane.\nNovara, Sept. 2 (UP) The gov\nernment has approved the merger\nof the Banca Popolare of Novara\nir.to the Credito Novarse bank.\nKILLED BY TROLLEY\nRockville, Sept, 2 George John\nston, 70, of Vernon, was killed yes\nterday afternoon when he walked\nout of a driveway and against tffB\nside of a Rockville bound Connecti\ncut company trolley car. He was\ndeaf and apparently did not hear\nthe warning whistle sounded by thu\nmbtorman.\nSlender, dark brown worms live\nin countless millions in the surface\nice\"of glaciers.\nBUSINESS REVIVAL\nLOOKED F(\nNew Spurt Predicted With\nComing o! Fall Season\nNew York, Sept. 2 (UP) Grow\ning confidence in predictions vof a\nsubstantial revival in business con\nditions during the falT' months was\nnoted in industrial and commercial\ncircles during the past week, al\nthough it is generally conceded by\nleading economists that trade revival\nonly awaits the development of the\nseasonal fall- buying movement.\nThe next few weeRs are expected\nto pr.ovide a test for business con\nditions. A survey of present condltious\nshows great irregularities. Offset\nting depressed conditions in the\nautomobile industrywhere the mar\nket is glutted with unsold new and\nused cars, a small increase has been\nmade in steel operations. The auto\ntire and accessory business is run-(\nning at a low ebb. the largest rub\nber company in the country,, thit\nweek reducing wages of office em\nployes. Prospective dividend reductions by\nmany companies, On the other hand,\nare expected to exercise at restrain\ning influence on the stock maYket.\nThere has yet, however, been little\nchange in the employment situa\ntion, and workers in many Indus\ntries are out of jobs. Inability of\nmany railroads to show fair profits\nso far this year has caused many of\nthem to suspend improvement pro\ngram. In many quarters it is believ\ned that only a substantial increase\nin motor production, regarded re\nmote at present, will serve to allay\nthe unemployment in many sections\nof the middle west. At the same\ntime, it is generally agreed that the\nLabor Day holiday marks the turn\ning perjod from the drastic summer\nshutdown.\nFlashes of Life 1\nBy th Associated Press.\nToronto George S. Lyon, who\nis 72 years old, still can shoot golf\nin the-\" 70's. In the first round of\nthe Championship of the Canadian\nSenior Golf association, he did 76,\nthree strokes better than the next.\nFlushing, N. Y. The first ride\nMrs. Anna Smith ever had on Long\nIsland was in an oxcart. The lat\nest is in an airplane. She is S5 years\nold.\nEast Setauket. N. Y. G. D.\nSmith, S5, of Crescent City, Fla.,\nVek\nave\ners\nWE CAN HELP YOU\nMany deserving men and women\nin this community have been\nhelped by our friendly loan serv\nice. And what we have done for\n'them we are willing and able to\ndo for others. If you have a\nfinancial problem, call and let us\nhelp you towards a happy solu\ntion. Reasonable rates. Con\nvenient terms.\n$10 to $300 Loans\nQuickly obtained Easily repaid\nTWEXTY MONTHS TO PAY\n2 Monthly Pays S 40 Loan\n5 Monthly Pays SI 00 Loan\n$10 Monthly Pays $200 Los,n\n$15 Monthly Pays $300 Loan\nThe entire cost is covered in an\ninterest charge of three and onc\ntolf per cent per month on the\nunpaid balance. There is no other\ncharge.\nPHONE 4950\nA Helpful Laaiprvice for the j\ns'Horae.''i-\nMutual System\nNew Leonard Building\ni j Room 202\nIJ 300 MAIN STREET\ni i i ii\nieiDea otrv\nhas been driving here annually with\nMrs. Smith to visit friends. y They\nmade the 1,300-mile motor trip on\nthe latest .visit In three days, travel\ning only between sunrise and sunset.\nBuenos! Aires High school girls\nof the suburb of Behjrano are on\nstrike because they have been warn-\"\ned not to appear in class with evi\ndence of use of rouge, lipstick or\neyebrow pencil.\nNew York The Rev. Dr. Harry\nEmerson Fosdick, pastor of the\nRiverside church, which John D.\nRockefeller, Jr., attends, gives no\ntice in a letter to members of the\ncongregation .lhat it might have a\nwholesome effect for the church to\nsay that people who do not care\nenough for worship to come on time\nmay not come at all. 1\nWashington The return of the\nbob is predicted; in fact, according\nto members arriving for the annual\nconvention of tfie National Hair\ndressers' and Cosmetologists' asso\nciation, it will be more popular than\never,\nLondon The Princ of Wales\nis getting on. He is now vice ad\nmiral, lieutenant general and air\nmarshal. The admiralty, the war\noffice and the air ministry announc\ned the promotions simultaneously.\nBerlin The prohibition Prty 's\none of 24 parties which will have\ncandidates on the ballot in the na\ntional election Sept. 14.\nNewport, R. I. Fifteen army\nmules who decided to take up gdlf\nhave been convinced that the ex\nclusive Newport Country club is no\nplace for them. They ambled from\nthe Fort Adams reservation and over\na stone wall onto the linksv -The\nrough, rather than greens and fair\nways, attracted them. Their A. W.\nO. L., was ended summarily before\nthey had taken many divots.\nRing Leaders Arrestedj\nWoman Sent to Prison\nCalcutta, Bengal, Sept. 2 W)\nSeveral men, believed to be ring\nleaders of the raid on the Chitta\ngong arsenal last April, were ar\nrested today after police had be\nsieged a house In Chandernagore, a\nFrench possession 30 miles north of\nCalcutta.\nMany shots were exchanged be\nfore the Negal police forced their\nSTERLING RANGE WEEK\nSTARTS TOMORROW\nA. IV J The PEER of AH A\nm Combination Ranges 11\nSpecial Sterling Week Offer\n1 ?20 ALLOWANCE for Your OLD STOVE.\n2 FREE CONNECTIONS Range Installed Ready to Use.\n3 EASIEST TERMS $10 Delivers Any-Sterling Range to Your\nome and' 18 Months to \"Pay \"trie balance.\nDaily Cooking Demonstrations\n\nMrs. Lillian Moore, home economics lecturer, will give daily cooking demonstra\ntions in our.window. She will give interesting, different Jalks on cooking. It will be\nwell worth your while to come in and hear her. Get one of Mrs. Moore's samples of\ncooking made on the Sterling Range King of the Bakers.\nway Into the \"house. The French\nauthorities gave special permits for\nthe polics; action.\nBombay, India, Sept. 2 W) Mrs.\nHansa Mohta, president of the\nBombay war council of1the $11 In\nylia national congress, and member\nof the congress working committee,\ntoday was sentenced to three months\nsimpleiimprisonment on a charge of\npublishing the congress bulletin.\nMr. Lele, vice president of the\ncouncil, i was sentenced to five\nmonths rigorous imprisonment for a\ncunilar offense.'\nARCH-MOXROE COLLISION\nCars driven by August Arendt\n120 Columbia street and James La\nm6nt.e of 27 Franklin street collided\nabout 6:30 o'clock last evening at\nMonroe and Arch streets, Arendt's\ncar being damaged slightly.- Officer\nNEW REDUCED RATES WITHIN CITY LIMITS\n50c\nAUBURN TAXI\n12 WASHINGTON STREET\n24 HOUR\nSavings -Bank of New Britain\nEstablished 1862\nResources -$25 ,148,427.88:\nDeposits Made on or Before Wednesday, September 3rd,\nWill Draw Interest From September 1st\nt\nINTEREST Being Paid\nThomas Blanchette reported that\nArendt was driving west on Monroe\nstreet and Lamonte was driving\nscuth on Arch street in a car owned\nbr Dominick Zita of V8 Franklin j\nstreet. Lamonte agreed to settle\nfor the damage.\nMan's Finger Is Cut v\nWhen Auto Turns Over\nRoyal Gray of East street sus\ntained a slight cut on the finger\nwhen an automobile in which he\nwas riding turned over while\nrounding the corner of Rocky Hill\navenue and Ellis street yesterday'\nafternoon. The were sixv passengers\nir. the car and Gray -was the only,\none injured.\nOH\nLouisiana had one automobile for1\neach 7.4 persons in the state last\nyear.\n\nSERVICE\nTELEPHONE 611\n1 The oven has automatic heat\ncontrol and can be kept at any\nv desired temperature. It bakes\nevenly in every part, as the burner\ncontrol keeps out cold air.\nThe \"VERTEX\" BROILER broils\nin half the time with half the\ngas.\n3 The \"KINDELATORf in the flre\nWox lights fires, helps warm the\nkitchen and hums up kitchen\ntrash.\n4 The WATER HEATER gives\nsteaming hot water quickly\n.with either coal or gas\n5 The 2-Heat Burner Snaps from\nlarge flame to small flame with a\nclick. Another click and flame\njumps up to full heat\n6 Tour KITCHEN will be warm in\nwinter cool in summer.\n7 ENAMEL cannot crack.\n8 FULLY GUARANTEED.\nBy J. P. McEVOY andJ. H. 